<dl id="s17020bb"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17020bb">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../ff/unbs/s17all.htm#s17020bb">sector 20(bb)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> dark heat, luminous heat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">These <font color="green">[facts]</font> tell us that a hot body, whether luminous like the sun or non-luminous like a hot stove, radiates heat in all directions. We may then distinguish between <i>invisible</i> or <mark><i>dark</i> rays that affect the nerves of the skin only, and <i>visible</i> or <i>luminous</i> rays</mark> that affect also the retina of the eye. <small> Wentworth and Hill, <a name="TBOP" href="/udra/udex.htm#tbop"><cite title="source">A Text-Book of Physics</cite></a> (1904), 131</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
